      <link>/manifesto/</link>
      <title>Manifesto</title>
      <pubDate>Mon, 02 Jun 2014 13:46:14 +0000</pubDate>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2 id="thekidsarealrightamanifesto">The Kids Are Alright: A Manifesto</h2>

<p>If there's an underlying motivation behind what I write here at Danielsaurus and why I write it, it's this simple idea: that <em>the kids are still alright these days</em>. </p>

<p>I see all children as capable, smart, caring, and curious, every one of them competent in their own ways – and each a valiant explorer of the world, if given the chance. Plenty of people have plenty of negative things to say about children and childhood today – and I've spent enough time with children themselves to know that most of it, simply, is just not true. So I want to put forth a different picture of things. I want to help children put their own voices out there, so that we can learn straight from them about their lives and cultures: about how they see the world, the trials and tribulations they may face, and what we, as adults, might be able to do to listen and understand them a bit better.</p>

<p>If there's a second idea behind Danielsaurus, it's this: at every point in their lives, <em>children are active and invested in approaching the world and interpreting it on their own terms</em>, within their own ways. They're anything but incomplete adults who must still learn the ways of the world – instead, they have worlds and cultures all of their own, that are separate, and frequently hidden, from us "grown-ups." They're creative in exploring their world, and they will actively resist any effort to diminish their world. And one of the most important things we can do to support them is recognize this – and offer a modicum of respect (and privacy) for their perspectives, places, and cultures.</p>

<p>And finally: <em>children are hardwired to explore and learn</em>. From the moment of their birth, children are truly voracious in their desire to engage in the world – exploring and engaging (if given the chance) in what interests them, actively constructing knowledge through their play and experiences, and diving in head first into challenges that they believe matter. Just like the rest of us, they experiment, make mistakes, and occasionally fail – eventually getting better through it all. And last, if given the chance – and the time, space, and freedom to do so – kids are capable of some truly incredible things. Why should we not try to see what they can do?</p>

<p>So that's my manifesto. I hope it seeps through everything you find here on Danielsaurus – and if any of all of that rings true for you personally, I truly hope that you will enjoy and read this blog regularly. (If that's something you already do, then from the bottom of my heart: thank you. It's nice to know you're reading.)</p>]]></content:encoded>
