      <title>Installment #24 of Kids Doing Awesome Things: Four African Teenagers Create a Pee-Powered Generator</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/11/the-latest-installment-of-kids-doing-awesome-things-four-african-teenagers-create-a-pee-powered-generator</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="http://static1.squarespace.com/static/501c8d6b24ac0a1285ed8244/501c8d6b24ac0a1285ed8259/509f3e6be4b039333cb51b47/1352613498395/8161674482_b25d1014c6_h.jpg" alt=""/>
  

<p>Wow. Well, that certainly wasn't a headline I was expecting to write today. As <a href="http://thenextweb.com/shareables/2012/11/07/forget-apps-and-other-useless-startups-these-four-african-girls-have-created-a-pee-powered-generator/">The Next Web</a> reports, though, 14-year-olds Duro-Aina Adebola, Akindele Abiola, Faleke Oluwatoyin, and 15-year-old Bello Eniola  from Nigeria have managed to invent... a urine-powered generator.</p><p>They're currently showcasing it at Maker Faire Africa, and one liter of pee is purported to provide six hours' worth of electricity. (The <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20167122">BBC is currently showing off</a> a few other innovations from the Maker Faire, too.)</p>

<p>Here's how the pee-generator works:</p>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
  <li>Urine is put into an electrolytic cell, which separates out the hydrogen.</li>
  <li>The hydrogen goes into a water filter for purification, which then gets pushed into the gas cylinder.</li>
  <li>The gas cylinder pushes hydrogen into a cylinder of liquid borax, which is used to remove the moisture from the hydrogen gas.</li>
  <li>This purified hydrogen gas is pushed into the generator.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<p>I have to say, those are some real <em>whiz</em> kids. (I'M SORRY! I'm sorry, okay? But that joke was inevitable.)</p>]]></content:encoded>
