      <link>/blog/2012/11/i-refuse-to-cater-to-the-bullshit-of-innocence</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>There's just too much to cherish in this <a href="http://www.believermag.com/issues/201211/?read=interview_sendak">late, wonderful, sprawling and idiosyncratic interview</a> with author and illustrator <a href="http://www.danielsaurus.com/blog?tag=Maurice+Sendak">Maurice Sendak</a>, who passed away this past year at age 83 – leaving the world one short a delightfully grumpy, Jewish, spiritual grandfather to us all.</p>

<p>If I had to pick a favorite passage from it, however, it'd be this one – a story Sendak shares in response to a question about the kinds of letters he likes to receive from children:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>When [children] write on their own, they’re ferocious. After <strong>Outside Over There</strong>, which is my favorite book of mine, a little girl wrote to me from Canada: "I like all of your books, why did you write this book, this is the first book I hate. I hate the babies in this book, why are they naked, I hope you die soon. Cordially…" Her mother added a note: "I wondered if I should even mail this to you—I didn’t want to hurt your feelings." I was so elated. It was so natural and spontaneous. The mother said, "You should know I am pregnant and she has been fiercely opposed to it." Well, she didn’t want competition, and the whole book was about a girl who’s fighting against having to look after her baby sister.</p>
  
  <p>BLVR: You find the unvarnished truth consoling, even if it’s vicious and painful.</p>
  
  <p>MS: If it’s true, then you can’t care about the vicious and the painful. You can only be astonished. Most kids don’t dare tell the truth. Kids are the politest people in the world. A letter like that is wonderful. "I wish you would die." I should have written back, "Honey, I will; just hold your horses."</p>
</blockquote>

<p>It's a fine example of the kind of honesty that Sendak cherished so much in life, and practiced so well himself. Though it led many to write about his "legendary crossness," Sendak in fact simply had an "impatience with artifice" – as his interviewer Emma Brockes notes. It was an impatience that he extended especially to matters of "Childhood." Sendak detested how adults would often treat children differently, and he believed the "bullshit of innocence" that was so firmly held to by many adults about children would often blind them from seeing the real emotions and intentions of children. Even more, Sendak recognized how children themselves often understood this, and eventually learned to take part in the complicated game of charades surrounding it. <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/09/maurice-sendak-on-the-first-book-hes-written-and-illustrated-in-30-years/245342/">In a 2011 interview in The Atlantic</a>, he shared this story to illustrate the lengths children will go to avoid disturbing their parents:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>I knew a little girl who told her parents – because her school was close by the twin towers when it happened – and she told her father that she saw the butterflies coming out of the windows. And only later said: "They weren't butterflies. They were people." But she lied, at first, to make him more comfortable. And that's what kids do – they are immensely courageous. And they sacrifice a lot. And they try to play mute and dumb because – well, it's kind of the expectation of their parents.</p>
  
  <p>That's what all the fairy tales are all mostly about – about the vulnerability of children and how they figure out tricks and ways of living in the world and making up parents. Make-believe parents. And I think that's probably one of the hardest jobs in the world. Being a parent, and not succumbing to failure. </p>
</blockquote>

<p>Of course, sometimes parents do get it right – as it is <a href="https://twitter.com/lettersofnote/status/199839306616020992">in this story</a>. Sendak had received a rather charming letter from a young boy, so he sent him back a postcard with a drawing of a wild thing. The boy's mother later wrote back to Sendak: "Jim loved your card so much he ate it." </p>

<p>He saw it, he loved it, he ate it.</p>

<p>That's the way it should be.</p>]]></content:encoded>
