      <title>How Kids Are Plotting to Take Over the World</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/11/another-fine-example-of-why-kids-rock</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The headline for this one about says it all: "Ethiopian Kids Hack OLPC Tablets in 5 Months with Zero Instruction."</p>

<p>There's quite a fascinating history behind the One Laptop Per Child (or OLPC) movement. As an organization, they've come a long way since its bold, yet controversial beginnings – its early years were mired in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Laptop_per_Child">geopolitical and international development debates</a>, and even arguments about what kind of software the laptops should run. OLPC's founder Nicholas Negroponte, though, <a href="http://www.technologyreview.com/view/429206/emtech-preview-another-way-to-think-about-learning/">clearly now has it nailed</a>. Self-organized learning is where it's at – and, through OLPC, we're now getting to see what a difference it makes when we simply trust children. Another great example of this can be found in Sugata Mitra's <a href="http://blog.ted.com/2012/01/24/new-ted-book-asks-can-changing-how-we-teach-make-our-kids-smarter-more-creative/">'Hole in the Wall' experiment</a>: where Mitra introduced, with no instruction, a networked PC within a (literal) hole in the wall, in an urban slum in New Dehli. Here's what he discovered afterward:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Experiments show that children in unsupervised groups are capable of answering questions many years ahead of the material they’re learning in school. In fact, they seem to enjoy the absence of adult supervision, and they are very confident of finding the right answer. Ultimately, they retain the learning effortlessly and for years, much longer than what we see with rote memorization of facts and figures. [...] Right now, we have a generation of children 16 years old or younger who have never known a world without many of the connecting technologies that we take for granted and rely on heavily. How do these devices affect, and even improve, how we absorb information? Self-organized learning would not work at all without the Internet. Educationists have suggested this type of instruction as a method for years, but the resources were not there until recently. Now, with the Internet, we have the means and the capabilities to watch self-organized learning flourish. It’s a very exciting time.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>An exciting time, indeed.</p>]]></content:encoded>
