      <title>The UK Boy Scouts Clamp Down on Nicknames</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/10/the-uk-boy-scouts-clamp-down-on-nicknames</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As part of an effort to prevent bullying, the UK Scout Association is issuing new guidelines to scoutleaders about the use of nicknames for children.</p>

<p>Their chief safeguarding officer Sam Marks explains:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>"Research and experience all highlight that name calling – whether it be nicknames or harmless taunting – is often the largest form of bullying. [...] If someone is called Frederick and you call them Freddie then there is no problem with that.</p>
  
  <p>"But you need to ask why that person has a nickname – if it is because they have red hair or are fat or they have a funny face, or because they did something funny and it stuck with them? They might be quite embarrassed by that."</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Interesting move on the Scout Association's part, to be sure – <a href="https://www.facebook.com/marc.armitage.play/posts/426233200772063">though as Marc Armitage asks</a>, "Are nicknames the same as hate-names?" I'm glad to see that many within the organization are thinking about what makes a nickname "good or bad", rather than simply issuing a blanket ban of using nicknames in general. And it's understandable that we adults would want to protect children from societal prejudice and hate; I personally wouldn't want to see adults introducing nicknames for children that are based on immutable personal characteristics or have negative connotations associated with them. In general, actually, I prefer adults follow children's lead about what they want to be called. That said, this whole nicknaming dilemma becomes a challenge when it is part of a broader effort on the part of adults (intentionally or not) to govern children's language and cultures.</p>

<p>One side to discussions like this one that is often left out or forgotten is the conceptual autonomy of children's cultures. We sometimes don't realize it, or think about it often, but children do have their own self-created, peer-based cultures that are separate from our adult culture – and the use of nicknames, shared lore and language, and other verbal play between children <a href="http://www.faqs.org/childhood/Me-Pa/Opie-Iona-and-Peter.html">typically assume a foundation role in these cultures</a>. They're all a sign of ownership and investment on the part of children, and they go alongside peer leadership, and secrecy, and child-controlled places as key elements of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Childhood_secret_club#Key_elements">children's secret clubs and special friendship groups</a>. And for us adults, it's often best we <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=D3x1FHpwrlsC&amp;pg=PA113&amp;lpg=PA113&amp;dq=making+a+place+in+the+curriculum&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=S8oh9YMNBx&amp;sig=9K6E2AOC5jm88vgvWacGjcMZqyY&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=MCyIUJO9BOjKiwKfsoH4Cg&amp;ved=0CD0Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&amp;q=making%20a%20place%20in%20the%20curriculum&amp;f=false">tread lightly</a> whenever we become involved in this aspect of children's lives and experiences. As David Sobel, a renowned educator and researcher of children's geographies, noted: </p>

<blockquote>
  <p>"Some aspects of children's lives are better left alone. Although it is a completely valid objective of progressive educators to relate the curriculum to the child's life, I have a sense that there are realms in which the adult should not trespass." </p>
  
  <p>– <em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/0814330266/?tag=danielsaurusrex-20">Children's Special Places: Exploring the Role of Forts, Dens, and Bush Houses in Middle Childhood</a></em> (p. 116)</p>
</blockquote>]]></content:encoded>
