      <title>A Brooklyn High School Embraces Tech-Based Vocational Education</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/10/a-brooklyn-high-school-embraces-tech-based-vocational-education</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>An inspiring example of what might hopefully lie ahead for secondary education:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>By 2017, the first wave of students of P-Tech — Pathways in Technology Early College High School — is expected to emerge with associate’s degrees in applied science in computer information systems or electromechanical engineering technology, following a course of studies developed in consultation with I.B.M.</p>
  
  <p>“I mean, in 10th grade, doing college work?” said Monesia McKnight, 15, as she sat in an introduction to computer systems course taught by a college professor. “How great is that?”</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Of course, P-Tech isn't without precedence: you need only look to <a href="http://www.edutopia.org/blog/vocational-education-benefits-mark-phillips">Finland and Norway's systems of public education</a> to see how well forward-thinking technical education like this has served their countries' young people.</p>]]></content:encoded>
