      <title>Boys Might Be Starting Puberty Earlier, Too</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/10/boys-might-be-starting-puberty-earlier-too</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>While a scientific consensus has developed in recent years that American girls are now hitting puberty earlier, on average, than the historic norm, a large study just released by the American Academy of Pediatrics suggests the same may be true for boys as well. Pam Belluck, reporting for the New York Times, offers a more nuanced look:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The study, widely considered the most reliable attempt to measure puberty in American boys, estimates that boys are showing signs of puberty six months to two years earlier than was reported in previous research, which historically taught that 11 ½ was the general age puberty began in boys. [...] </p>
  
  <p>The study, which was to be announced at the Academy of Pediatrics national conference on Saturday and published online in the journal Pediatrics, did not try to determine what might be causing earlier puberty, although it mentioned changes in diet, less physical activity and other environmental factors as possibilities. Experts said that without further research, implications for boys are unclear.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The primary message first and foremost, according to the study's authors and other experts, should be one of cautious curiosity: while the study provides usful new data for those in the pediatric and urology fields, "the study should not prompt a magazine 'cover article that shows a 9-year-old boy shaving,'" Ms. Belluck cites one expert as saying.</p>

<p>One of the more interesting issues associated with earlier puberty onset for both boys and girls, however, are the social ramifications. Whatever our views on the subject are, I believe most Americans (and American culture by and large) do not deal well with perceived disparities between children's biological development and our own social constructions of childhood. Maggie Koerth-Baker addresses the difficulties that can accompany this especially well, I think, <a href="http://boingboing.net/2012/10/20/boys-might-be-hitting-puberty.html">over at Boing Boing</a>:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Even if both boys and girls are hitting puberty earlier, scientists acknowledge that the social results are very, very different. Parents don't particularly care when their 9-year-old son's testicles get bigger. Parents are deeply concerned when their 9-year-old daughter grows breasts. And with good reason. Even if a woman otherwise looks very young, people start treating her differently once the boobs kick in — "differently" in ways that can be really problematic for a 9-year-old. I had a friend in grade school who had breasts by 4th or 5th grade. She'd get cat-called on the street by grown men. </p>
</blockquote>]]></content:encoded>
