      <title>The Force is Still with 'Star Wars'</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/10/the-evergreen-appeal-of-star-wars-for-a-new-generation</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Alan Greenblatt shares about the everlasting appeal of Star Wars – now being enjoyed by a young generation of kids, many of whom have never even seen the original films:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>There's no mystery to why Star Wars remains popular with young boys, says Robert Thompson, a pop culture professor at Syracuse University. It's got just about everything they like — spaceships, creatures that look like dinosaurs, creatures that look like teddy bears.</p>
  
  <p>"The films are exquisitely simple and executed in a way so that they're user-friendly to a kid," he says. [...]</p>
  
  <p>The depth of Star Wars' imaginative world is a major part of the attraction. Lots of young boys can rattle off information about the differences between spaceships or entire galaxies without having seen any of the movies.</p>
  
  <p>"Boys versed in Star Wars share a private language about a vast technical universe that is simultaneously imaginary and concrete, re-created in Lego plastic blocks," Paglia says in an email interview.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Wait, he's talking about kids – not grown adults? Oh. Um... Yeahhhhh, maybe I like Star Wars too much.</p>

<p>(Oh, and don't miss <a href="http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2012/10/04/star-wars-opens-at-the-coronet-are-you-in-these-1977-photos/">this great photo recollection</a> of the  1977 opening of of the original <em>Star Wars</em> film. I wish I were old enough to be in those photographs!)</p>]]></content:encoded>
