      <title>Don’t Mess With Big Bird</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/10/dont-mess-with-big-bird</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Charles M. Blow:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Since 1969, Big Bird has been the king of the block on “Sesame Street.” When I was a child, he and his friends taught me the alphabet and the colors and how to do simple math. [...] </p>
  
  <p>And, for me, it’s bigger than Big Bird. It’s almost impossible to overstate how instrumental PBS has been in my development and instruction.</p>
  
  <p>We were poor. My mother couldn’t afford day care, and I didn’t go to preschool. My great-uncle took care of me all day. I could watch one hour of television: PBS.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Never underestimate the power of the intangible in a society, like public television. In a land built on the promise of opportunity, the public goods and services that are there for the benefit of all can truly make an endless difference. </p>

<p>Count me with Mr. Blow when he says: "I honestly don’t know where I would be in the world without PBS."</p>]]></content:encoded>
