    <item>
      <title>Who's Really Getting Robbed?</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/9/whos-really-getting-robbed</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Michael Winerip gets straight to the point:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The only way to save America’s children is to lock up the baby boomers. We are robbing the next generation’s future.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Except... it's more complicated than that, as Winerip later ventures to explain in his essay. It's an interesting read, and as an exercise it is propelled by the kind of back-and-forth internal dialogue and overall questioning that is needed whenever "the plight of millenials" (and/or their laziness, lack of work ethic, parental clinginess, and general inability to "grow up" – all depending on who you listen to) is considered.</p>

<p>Let's cut straight to the reality here: it is completely a matter of apples-and-oranges thinking to put millenials up against any other generation to compare. Millenials are not like older generations, and are simply never going to be – because <em>the world they've grown up in and now inhabit</em> isn't the same as it was for other generations. In order to even begin to compare generations and examine their differences, you first have to reevaluate the frames of reference you use for such a comparison. And when the world moves so fast, and changes so much, it becomes pretty impossible to establish any kind of meaningful insight into why millenials are the  way they are.</p>

<p>A better question – and the question that at least initially drove the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generation">social sciences-rooted generation studies</a> movement – is how the social and economic structures of a society have changed for this new group of individuals. At its best, "generational" thinking and cohort-based research may yield useful insight into the unique cultural contexts and circumstances that those of a specific generation have generally experienced together. When you turn it into this superficial, mass pop-psychology examination of the personity traits and characteristics of all people of a similar age, though, that's little better than relying on race or gender to determine who you think a person is; simply put, it's <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generationism">institutionalized discrimination</a> – shamelessly brandished under the guise of "research." And it's just plain wrong, any way you slice it.</p>

<p>(And now in other news... Apparently, I'm turning into the "get off my lawn, you darn old people!" character for the millenial generation. Um, okay?)</p>]]></content:encoded>
