    <item>
      <title>Ordinary People and Hope</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/9/ordinary-people-and-hope</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>One of Andrew Sullivan's readers writes in to respond to criticism of President Obama's convention speech:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>I wish that the pundits would watch these speeches with ordinary people. Last night I watched the speech with a gathering of about 50 people, from junior-high age to seniors. Everyone loved the speech. The most important thing for me from his speech was that he was challenging us to be grown ups and offering a vision of a people who are united and proud of the contributions they make to each other. [...] Last night you heard a President tell a nation that they must be tough, work hard, and contribute to something greater than themselves. You heard a President tell us that our founding values and the sacrifices of generations demanded that we be good citizens. You heard a President express his love for his people regardless of party or ideology. [...] </p>
  
  <p>My middle son watched the speech with me and was cheering because he sees in our President a person who is a role model and that gives him hope. He signed up to phone bank. My oldest son texted me to say that the speech was incredible and that he was moved by the way that he brought us back to hope - a mature hope that is grounded in service to others.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I can't recall another president in recent past who has been as much of a role model to young people as Barack Obama has today. Political views aside, screw the pundits and politicians who say that the young people who turned out in force in 2008 are simply not going to care anymore because they don't have jobs. What draws our admiration of Obama is something much deeper than that; it's about values and optimism over the long haul, and more than anything it's about desiring to do good and help others – to leave the world a little better off, rather than just care about ourselves.</p>]]></content:encoded>
