      <title>Kids Explain Modern Art</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/9/kids-take-you-on-a-tour-of-modern-art</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It's "an unofficial audio tour" of the Museum of Modern Art in NYC, narrated solely by kids (via <a href="http://kottke.org/12/09/moma-audio-tours-narrated-by-kids">Kottke</a>):</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Each piece of art is analyzed by experts aged 3-10, as they share their unique, unfiltered perspective on such things as composition, the art's deeper meaning, and why some stuff's so weird looking. This is Modern Art without the pretentiousness, the pomposity, or any other big "p" words.</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>My short response:</strong> Now <em>that's</em> how you look at art.</p>

<p><strong>My real response:</strong> As cool as this is, I would have loved for the audio clips to be longer, and the children given more opportunity to think about and explain the paintings. An approach like <a href="http://vtshome.org">Visual Thinking Strategies</a> could've been employed perfectly here; believe it or not, children <em>are</em> capable of incredible in-depth thinking and articulation, and I sometimes wonder if these 'soundbite'-y sorts of projects only perpetuate an expectation for adults not to take children too seriously.</p>]]></content:encoded>
