      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Dr. Samuel Weinstein, a pediatric cardiothoracic surgeon, shares what it's like to give a child a new heart:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>There are certainly more difficult procedures in congenital cardiac surgery to perform than a heart transplant, but few freighted with more anticipation. After all, the heart that we are asking to sustain our patient started off this morning in another child. The transplant cardiologist who has been taking care of this child for the last year meets us in the O.R. at 4:15 a.m. “How is it going?” she asks.</p>
  
  <p>After the heart is sewn in and we allow it to be perfused with blood, it starts to beat. Within 30 minutes, it is beating strongly enough that the patient can come off the heart-lung machine. The boy is on his own.</p>
</blockquote>]]></content:encoded>
