      <title>Maria Montessori's Influence Over Google</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/9/maria-montessoris-influence-over-google</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Today, Google honors the legacy of educator Maria Montessori with one of their special homepage doodles. In fact, it's fairly well known that Google's two co-founders attended Montessori schools during their childhoods – and that upbringing may have had more of an influence over who they would become, and the company they would found, than you may realize. Marissa Mayer shares further:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>“You can’t understand Google unless you know that both Larry and Sergey were Montessori kids,” Levy explained. “She’s referring to schools based on the education philosophy of Maria Montessori, an Italian physician born in 1870 who believed that children should be allowed the freedom to pursue their interests.”</p>
  
  <p>“In a Montessori school, you go paint because you have something to express or you just want to do it that afternoon, not because the teacher said so,” articulated Mayer. “This is baked into how Larry and Sergey approach problems. They’re always asking, why should it be like that? It’s the way their brains were programmed early on.”</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Look around at the people changing the world and I guarantee you those will be the misfits and rebels, the ones who dropped out of high school or never attended a "real" one to begin with. To steal a quip from Apple and Steve Jobs, to think differently requires that you be educated differently, too.</p>]]></content:encoded>
