    <item>
      <title>Let Your Kids Do Stupid Things. And Let Yourself Do Them, Too.</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/on-taking-risks-and-making-mistakes-essential-experiences-for-kids-psychology-today</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Peggy Drexler has an essay I've been sitting on for quite a while. An author and psychologist who focuses on gender and family issues, she wrote a column several months ago that was passionate and effective plea for why we should let our children take risks and make mistakes. It's <a href="http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/our-gender-ourselves/201208/taking-risks-and-making-mistakes-essential-experiences-kids">well worth reading</a>, it should go without saying, and it addresses the sensitive balance that we need to strike when supporting children's in their mistakes: reliable and observant, though not interfering. Comfortable with uncertainty and patient with children's timing. Encouraging of their exploration, while providing an emotional safety to return to. Drexler's essay ends with mismatched socks – but all the while, it left me curious about <em>why</em> we as adults are so uncomfortable with children's need to take risks and make mistakes, even as we might match up those same needs with a different importance and understanding in our own lives.</p>

<p>Maybe this isn't true for everybody: but I think most of us (adults, that is) inherently recognize that there is something necessary – and perhaps even virtuous – about challenging yourself. About making mistakes to learn from, about testing hypotheses about situations, and about taking risks, physically, intellectually, and socially. These are essential experiences in most of our lives, and deep down I think many of us recognize the role they play in living a happy and contented life. </p>

<p>So where is it along the way, in the crazy process of growing up, that so many of us adults forget these apply to children just as equally? Do we really tell ourselves that kids shouldn't face problems, or be allowed to summon their own strength and courage and face their problems independently? When did our "grown up" experiences of risktaking and challenge suddenly become so separate, so manifestly different from what they were like when we were kids? We just don't seem to connect the two anymore; it's like the distance between children's risktaking and the risktaking of adults is miles apart, so wide in fact that we've completely forgotten all of the feelings of what it was like before. How have we gotten to this point?</p>

<p>I really don't know. </p>

<p>I have a hunch, though. I think that this illusion of separation first begins to take hold when we stop living our lives alongside our children, and focus instead on managing their own lives. Instead of embracing the serendipitous with children, we run off to the bookshelf first to see what Dr. Spock and ther other "child experts" say about it. We get caught up in the Parenting Magazine version of how our children's lives "need to" be. We trap ourselves in questioning whether we're being a "good parent." And we cling fiercely to the "childhood" we think is right.</p>

<p>All the while, children are living their lives without us, right before our eyes.</p>]]></content:encoded>
