      <title>Returning 'Baby Veronica' to Her Native American Tribe</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/returning-baby-veronica-to-her-native-american-tribe</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Marcia Zug, a law professor writing for Slate, offers a compelling look at a recent, sensationalized adoption story from South Carolina: that of Veronica, a young 2-year-old Cherokee Indian child who was adopted at birth and returned to her biological father earlier this year by the state, despite protest from her adoptive parents. </p>

<p>The adoptive parents, who had Veronica for nearly two years, have been fighting fiercely to regain custody of her since she was returned – bringing incredible media attention to the case in the process. On July 26, though, the South Carolina Supreme Court  affirmed the decision for her return, citing how Veronica's initial adoption was in clear violation of a federal statute known as the Indian Child Welfare Act.</p>

<p>This case may seem tragic – yet as Zug later explains, it is heartwrenching in more ways than one. As tragic as the experience may be for the adoptive family, the South Carolina Supreme Court was also absolutely right in its decision. In order to understand why, though, you have to know and understand the Indian Child Welfare Act. And for that, you should read this article. </p>

<p>It's a tough thing to have a kid placed in a scenario like this – but the world is a messy place, and when you place things like this within the context of history and the law, you realize we often just have to live with it.</p>]]></content:encoded>
