      <title>A Legal Battle Ensues Over Same-Sex Classrooms in Public Schools</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/legal-battle-over-same-sex-classes-in-public-schools</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Here's another education tactic to file away under 'Trying to Solve the Wrong Problem in the Wrong Way, for the Wrong Reason': in this case, a public middle school in West Virginia is now facing a lawsuit brought on by the American Civil Liberties Union for allegedly practicing gender discrimination, based on how it sets up and implements instruction within the school's same-sex classrooms. </p>

<p>Abigail Pesta, writing for The Daily Beast, reports:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The suit, filed on behalf of a mother of three daughters who attend the school, contends, among other things, that the school lights its classrooms more brightly for boys than for girls—and encourages boys to move around freely throughout the day and girls to sit quietly and share their feelings.</p>
  
  <p>“The school is dividing kids based on reproductive organs,” says Amy Katz, an attorney working with the ACLU.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>While same-sex classrooms are legal in America – and have been growing in number since 2006, when many federal restrictions against them were relaxed – they are not without controversy. Proponents argue that teaching boys and girls separately allows educators to more fully address what they see as issues that are gender-specific to students – in so doing helping all children "reach their full potential." Opponents, however, argue that their practices are based on little more than pseudoscience and gender stereotypes, and perpetuate sexism. Pesta covers the issue well, and to be sure there are valid opinions on both sides.</p>

<p>That said, this is so astoundingly, overwhelmingly an example of solving the wrong problem in the wrong way, for the wrong reasons. All children are different; gender is just one aspect of this, and it is largely a socially constructed one at that (but we'll get into that later). Rather than having an education system that separates children because of their differences, how infinitely richer it would be to have schools that not only welcomed but celebrated these differences – embracing each child as an individual, with a pedagogy that draws upon their strengths and doesn't limit their education to just "the way boys learn" and "the way girls learn". How about we make it instead about "the way Jacob learns, and the way Suzy learns, and the way John learns"?</p>

<p>Gender's not the problem here: it's the pedagogy that's the problem.</p>]]></content:encoded>
