      <title>U.S. Kids Increasingly Opting for Diet Soda Drinks, 'Just Like Mom And Dad'</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/us-kids-increasingly-opting-for-diet-soda-drinks-just-like-mom-and-dad</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>NPR reports:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>In fact, consumption of diet drinks has doubled among U.S. children over a decade. About 1 in 4 of adults drink low-calorie or no-calorie sweetened drinks and foods. And for children: Six percent were consuming diet drinks in 1999-2000. This increased to 12.5 percent in 2007-2008. The findings were recently published in The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>On the surface, it's certainly an interesting trend. More importantly, though, I think it highlights the importance of not treating children's health and childhood obesity as a separate issue from the rest of society. The reality is children's health is most closely correlated with their parents' health: parents that are active and eat (and drink) healthily have children who are active and healthy as well.</p>]]></content:encoded>
