      <title>Misplaced Mondays, August 20th Edition</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/misplaced-mondays-1</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Starting, well, today, we have a new feature here at Danielsaurus: the “everything we forgot to post this past week and are too attention-deficit to go back and post this week, but should probably share anyway” feature. It’s a round-up of stories from the past few weeks that might've gone overlooked or underappreciated – or perhaps just forgotten, but are definitely still worth your while. This gives me no excuse now not to link to more things, so I hope you enjoy the added bits of delight every Monday.</p>

<p>Here you go!</p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Just another princess movie?</strong> <a href="http://5by5.tv/incomparable/102">A geeky discussion on the 5by5 podcast network</a> on what Pixar’s new film “Brave” – and Disney’s many past princess movies – say <a href="http://thenewinquiry.com/essays/just-another-princess-movie/">about female characters in animation and film in general</a>.</p>

<p>Via <a href="https://www.facebook.com/bellellied/posts/429252833793093">Bellelli Educación</a>, <a href="http://www.melindawenner.com/Clips_files/MiQ109Wenn2p.pdf">a 2009 article in Scientific American</a> explores how <strong>children use more sophisticated language when playing with other children</strong> than when playing with adults.</p>

<p><strong>In your twenties, gay, and settled in your relationship? Bring on the baby expectations.</strong> <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/10/us/gay-couples-face-pressure-to-have-children.html?pagewanted=all">Nowadays, even gay couples are facing the pressure to have children</a>.</p>

<p><strong>Having iPads in the classroom raises math scores by 49%</strong>, according to <a href="http://www.eschoolnews.com/2012/06/27/kipp-academy-flips-the-8th-grade-math-classroom-using-yourteacher-on-the-ipad/">one program evaluation</a> (Via <a href="http://www.loopinsight.com/2012/08/13/ipads-in-the-classroom-raise-math-scores-49/">Loop Insight</a>). You could probably argue this has more to do with the <a href="http://www.edutopia.org/blog/flipped-classroom-best-practices-andrew-miller">Flipped Classroom pedagogy</a> behind it, but nonetheless it’s a stirring example of how technology can be used to empower children as learners.</p>

<p>A flashback to the past: <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/2012/aug/12/from-the-archive-junk-playground-1953?newsfeed=true">a 1953 report in the UK’s Observer</a> on <strong>how two of London’s adventure playgrounds are giving children a much-needed space for youthful adventure</strong>.</p>

<p>Capitalizing on the famed director’s birthday, Maria Popova shares <strong><a href="http://www.brainpickings.org/index.php/2012/08/13/happy-birthday-hitchcock-how-the-iconic-director-changed-one-boys-life/">how Alfred Hitchcock made an indelible impact on one young boy’s life</a></strong>.</p>

<p><strong>How do you make the decision about when your child is old enough for his or her first cellphone?</strong> <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/09/technology/personaltech/weighing-when-a-child-is-old-enough-for-a-cellphone.html?emc=tnt&amp;tntemail1=y">It’s a tricky issue.</a> I should comment on this separately, but I’ll take a stab here anyway: while the article suggests avoiding smartphones for specialized “family”-based phones, I’d argue for the exact opposite: giving a kid a GPS-enabled smartphone, like the iPhone, opens up a world of geographic exploration and mobility. Mike Lanza has <a href="http://playborhood.com/2010/06/give_mobile_phones_to_tweens_then_let_them_roam/">a great piece on this exact issue over at Playborhood</a>.</p>

<p><strong><a href="http://www.brothers-brick.com/2012/08/10/mission-to-mars-an-interview-with-stephen-pakbaz/">Build with LEGO, send a Rover to Mars</a></strong>. A great interview with Stephen Pakbaz, one of the designers of the Curiosity rover, reflecting on his LEGO-filled childhood. Via <a href="http://io9.com/5933865/behold-a-lego-curiosity-rover-built-by-a-designer-of-the-real-curiosity?tag=thisisawesome">This is Awesome</a>.</p>

<p>And finally, if you weren’t convinced already, Glenda Cooper makes <strong><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/9455881/Tiger-mums-its-best-to-underparent.html">a very good argument for why you should ditch helicopter parenting</a></strong> in exchange for something a little less drastic.</p>]]></content:encoded>
