      <title>"Come off it, folks: how many paedophiles can there be?"</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/come-off-it-folks-how-many-paedophiles-can-there-be</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Quite amazingly, that rather forthright declaration is the real title of an op-ed in England's The Telegraph newspaper, published originally in 2006. The op-ed's author? None other than Boris Johnson, now the Mayor of London. He was asked to move seats while on a British Airways flight because he was sitting next to two kids – his <em>own</em>, ironically, though the stewardess didn't realize this at first. And as Johnson highights, he hasn't been the only adult male unjustifiably accused of pedophilia, simply by virtue of being around children.</p>

<p>Johnson might be a loveably daft fellow most days, but his perspective is spot on in this case – his outrage aptly justified, in my humble opinion. This preoccupation that both American and British societies have with pedophilia – which continues to be ungrounded in any statistical reality – really does just puzzle my mind, and more concertingly detracts from actual efforts to prevent real child abuse. If only more of us would take the time, as Johnson did, to call out the hysteria for what it is: an unfounded, unhelpful moral panic.</p>

<p>Via <a href="http://www.theagitator.com/2012/08/15/come-off-it-folks-how-many-paedophiles-can-there-be/">Lenore Skenazy, of Free-Range Kids</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
