      <title>Feds Seek Action Against Mississippi's 'School-to-Prison Pipeline'</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/the-feds-go-after-mississippis-school-to-prison-pipeline</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The U.S. Justice Department is accusing Lauderdale County, Mississippi, of violating students' rights by not giving them an opportunity for due process:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Officials in Lauderdale County, Mississippi, have operated "a school-to-prison pipeline" that violates the constitutional rights of juveniles by incarcerating them for alleged school disciplinary infractions, some as minor as defiance, the U.S. Department of Justice said Friday. "Students most affected by this system are African-American children and children with disabilities," the Justice Department said. [...]</p>
  
  <p>"The systematic disregard for children's basic constitutional rights by agencies with a duty to protect and serve these children betrays the public trust," Thomas E. Perez, assistant U.S. attorney general, said in a statement. "We hope to resolve the concerns outlined in our findings in a collaborative fashion, but we will not hesitate to take appropriate legal action if necessary."</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Lauderdale County's "school-to-prison" pipeline has been the subject of a consistent stream of criticism over the years, as well as a federal class-action lawsuit by the Southern Poverty Law Center in 2009 that alleged that "children and teens were subjected to 'shockingly inhumane' treatment." Amongst other rights violations that the County was found at fault for, police officials within the schools used pepper spray and Mace on students as punishment for infractions as minor as "talking too much".</p>

<p>Needless to say, it's great to see that the feds are taking action against such a corrupt and violent system.</p>]]></content:encoded>
