      <title>Teaching and Raising Disobedient Children</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/teaching-and-raising-disobedient-children</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<figure>
  <blockquote>
    <span>&#147;</span>Disobedience is not an issue if obedience is not the goal.<span>&#148;</span>
  </blockquote>
  <figcaption class="source">&mdash; Daron Quinlan</figcaption>
</figure><p>Tom Hobson – or as he is better known, <a href="http://teachertomsblog.blogspot.com">Teacher Tom</a> – has been writing online for a long time, using his blog as a continual reflection on the more philosophical aspects of a life shared with a bunch of three- and four-year-olds. His writings have always struck me me as a sort of encapsulation of the universe: not only, though, has Teacher Tom's blog been an outlet for exploring the joys of life through the eyes of the young, who are experiencing it afresh, vividly and directly – but it is a testament to what adults can learn and discover about the world through children. In Teacher Tom's world, adults and children alike take an active and equal part in this discovery.</p>

<p>It's posts like this one – entitled <a href="http://teachertomsblog.blogspot.com/2012/08/how-to-make-adults-who-will-not-be.html">'How to Make Adults Who Will Not Be Pushed Around'</a> – where Tom really gets to to the heart of the matter of life with children, though. As he begins:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>I have never been interested in obedient children. They tend to either grow into rebellious teens who are a danger to themselves as they try to "make up for" all that time spent living under a regimen of artificially repressed urges, or perhaps worse, obedient adults who are a danger to the rest of us.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I don't think we consider enough the longer-term impacts of our actions when we teach and parent children. As adults, we have extraordinary power over them – almost undoubtedly undeserved power, most of the time, but power we have to consider and contend with nonetheless. If we don't think about how we use and manage this power, and about how we can keep it from monopolizing our interactions with children, we run a great risk in the kinds of messages we send them about life. </p>

<p>In the stories, the real heroes are always the ones who don't seek out power: they have it forced on them, with untold responsibilities along with it – and in the good stories, the hero's struggle is never really against the villain, but about the unchecked abuse of his or her power. In the end, the successful heroes find a way to put it back in the hands of the people – back in the hands of whom it really belongs. I think the same could be said for us as teachers and parents.</p>

<p>As Tom continues:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>As a teacher, I am always looking for ways to give away whatever power is implied by that title, to let the children be in charge of their own learning, of their own bodies, of their own small society. I want them to make the "right" decisions, not because I've told them so, but because they have learned through experience that it is the right decision. I want them to know that they are always responsible for their own behavior. I want them to know that their feelings, their thoughts, and their opinions are just as important as anyone else's. I want them to know, most of all, that this is true even for people with who are stronger, more powerful or wealthier. I want them to grow to be adults who make their own decisions and will not be pushed around.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>It is foolish to pretend that we don't have power over children as adults. But we also have to recognize that we're only temporary guardians of this power – and in time it will slip out of our grasp and find its way into others' hands. Far better to give it away before that, in a way that respects and empowers children – letting them grow into the capable and competent adults the world needs – than to let ourselves become corrupted by that power.</p>]]></content:encoded>
