    <item>
      <title>'On Kids and How to Help Them Grow'</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/ben-delaney-on-kids-and-how-to-help-them-grow</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Ben Delaney reminisces on parenting his children:</p><blockquote><span>I’ve adopted a new parenting philosophy over the last couple years, and a big part of it boils down to this: treat kids like they are capable of being strong, making decisions, and being generally “alive in the world”. Doing so instills more confidence and self-respect than protecting them from imaginary danger and shielding them from risk ever could. My kids are 9 and 5. We go to the woods as often as we can (at least once a week this time of year). We run and climb and play. I very purposefully do not tell them where to go or what to do. I don’t call them back when they start to wander. We just play and do. Having done this dozens of times now, I know the secret: they want to stay close to me. Sometimes they want to lead the way, and they do; other times I lead because they know that I know the way better. Minor cuts and bruises are rubbed off, spit on, and acknowledged for what they are, nothing more. Trees and rocks are for climbing and we climb them. Rope swings are for swinging, and rivers are for swimming.</span></blockquote><blockquote><span>The more I expose them to these environments (that most parents would consider “dangerous”), the more they respect them. They almost always self-regulate — if something is too big to try, they tend to not try it. If something is new, they come find me and ask for help, and we figure it out slowly, together. When we scramble along on the edge of the high cliffs, they don’t act squirly. We’ve already crawled up to the edge together and peered down into that void. I don’t have to tell them, they know it’s dangerous. They have a built-in respect for where they are and they play within the natural boundaries that they feel safe within. They almost never need to be told “be careful.” Honestly, it’s kind of amazing.<br></span></blockquote><p><span>Do read the full thing – and read the piece Ben links to about Swiss forest kindergartens; they both get to the heart of just so many good things about living life peacefully with children. The purpose of parenting has never been to protect your kids or shield them from the larger world. Instead, it's simply been to provide them with a safe place to explore from and then come back to at the end of the night, after their adventures – a place where they can find dinner still waiting for them, hot as ever.</span></p>]]></content:encoded>
      <excerpt:encoded />
      <wp:post_name>2012/8/ben-delaney-on-kids-and-how-to-help-them-grow</wp:post_name>
      <wp:post_type>post</wp:post_type>
      <wp:post_id>191</wp:post_id>
      <wp:status>publish</wp:status>
