      <title>The Dangers of “Oh, Grow Up”</title>
      <link>/blog/2011/9/2/oh-grow-up</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>John Boehner and Barack Obama engage in a very public battle over the timing of a speech, each side aiming thinly-veiled vitriol at the other, and the New York Times editorial board (rightly) decries it as political spectacle. But under what headline does the newspaper title and run the piece?</p>

<p><em>“Oh, grow up.”</em></p>

<p>The subtle, probably unintentional implication here is that Boehner and Obama are acting petulently, and only children act that way. It's a slippery, almost elusive slight – but absolutely powerful. You can't help but discriminate against children when you suggest ill-mannered behavior isn’t “grown up.” </p>

<p>We need to remember, though, that age and maturity aren't necessarily correlated things. A good many young children can display incredibly maturity, while many old men can be petty and arrogant, much as John Boehner here.</p>

<p>So, to the New York Times: instead of labeling this behavior as “childish” – or ascribing it to those who need to “grow up” or “act their age” – let’s stop demeaning kids and label this behavior what it really is: just plain immaturity. It’s as simple as that.</p>]]></content:encoded>
