      <title>Bill Watterson on Children and Parents</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/4/zsngyf10pch7gxvymz5zghxg62x1xw</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>“Calvin and Hobbes” creator Bill Watterson, in a rare Q&amp;A exchange that took place in 2005:</p><blockquote><p>Q: What attributes do you wish were seen more commonly among children?</p><p>A: Good parents!</p></blockquote><p>Typical for Bill Watterson: a simple, direct, even mousy response – but unexpectedly truthful. I was caught off guard by it at first, actually, thinking about how most people would likely reel off &nbsp;a long answer to the question. Of course Watterson would see it from the kids’ side, though; leave it him to recognize that many of the problems children children – and the deficiencies we like to find in children – actually have their roots in the failings and indifference of the adults around them instead.</p>]]></content:encoded>
