      <title>'How to Talk to Little Girls'</title>
      <link>/blog/2011/8/how-to-talk-to-little-girls</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Yes, it seems ridiculous that you'd need even instructions for this. But, as Lisa Bloom explores, our speech when interacting with young children can have a profound effect on gender roles and what we expect from children. In short: the <em>"Ahhh, look at the cute little girl!" </em>icebreaker talk just ain't gonna cut it. Bloom&nbsp;suggests something different:</p><blockquote><p>Try this the next time you meet a little girl. She may be surprised and unsure at first, because few ask her about her mind, but be patient and stick with it. Ask her what she’s reading. What does she like and dislike, and why? There are no wrong answers. You’re just generating an intelligent conversation that respects her brain. For older girls, ask her about current events issues: pollution, wars, school budgets slashed. What bothers her out there in the world? How would she fix it if she had a magic wand? You may get some intriguing answers. Tell her about your ideas and accomplishments and your favorite books. Model for her what a thinking woman says and does.</p></blockquote>]]></content:encoded>
