    <item>
      <title>Fraser Speirs: 'How the iPad Wants to Be Used'</title>
      <link>/blog/2011/1/fraser-speirs-how-the-ipad-wants-to-be-used</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Last autumn, a small school in Scotland abandoned classroom computers almost entirely – leaving behind the&nbsp;aging notion of 'the school IT lab' along with them.</p><p>Instead, each child in the school was given an iPad – and since then, the move has transformed the ways the students and teachers integrate technology into classroom learning within the school. Fraser Speirs, the IT guy and technology teacher at the school who was the driving force behind the change, did the world an excellent deed by documenting the entire process: from the small, quirky technical decisions they faced implementing the change to the giant shifts in ideology and thinking about technology that the adults at the school experienced. (Of course needless to say, the kids themselves didn’t have any problem whatsoever adapting to the change.)</p><p>It’s a great series, very honest and self-reflective – a perfect way to understand the potential for well-designed technology within education while recognizing the nuance and challenge of "doing it right."</p><p></p>]]></content:encoded>
