      <title>Common Ground on Abortion</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/common-ground-on-abortion</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In his regular column for the Washington Post, E.J. Dionne recently wrote about&nbsp;<a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-%20dyn/content/article/2009/05/17/AR2009051701773.html">a recent speech President Barack Obama gave</a>&nbsp;at the University of Notre Dame – a speech that specifically and meaningfully addressed the topic of abortion. Dionne reflects:<br></p><blockquote><p>￼Facing down protesters who didn’t want him at Notre Dame, President Obama fought back not with harsh words but with the most devastating weapons in his political arsenal: a call for “open hearts,” “open minds,” “fair-minded words” and a search for “common ground.”</p><p>There were many messages sent from South Bend. Obama’s opponents seek to reignite the culture wars. He doesn’t. They would reduce religious faith to a narrow set of issues. He refused to join them. They often see theological arguments as leading to certainty. He opted for humility.</p></blockquote><p>Too often, the topic of abortion in America is treated as a battle.</p><p>Many of my friends know my stance on this. It’s something I can get pretty passionate about – not because I hold strongly to any one position that I feel is right, but because of how poorly I feel people understand the statistical and sociological realities of abortion. It shocks me – disgusts me, even – how quickly these realities about abortion can be oversimplified or dwarfed by dogma. But when we finally face the realities of abortion, we must confront these statistics:</p><ol><li>Making abortion illegal&nbsp;<a href="http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/fb_induced_abortion.pdf">has no impact on the number of abortions performed</a>. In fact, the countries with the lowest rates of abortion also have the most open and supportive laws regarding abortion.</li><li>A shocking&nbsp;<a href="http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/fb_induced_abortion.pdf">75% of abortions are driven primarily by economic reasons</a>&nbsp;– simply, women donʼt feel they can financially afford to raise a child or will have the necessary support to do so.</li><li>Finally,&nbsp;<a href="http://www.catholicsinalliance.org/files/CACG_Final.pdf">social and economic supports do more to reduce abortion rates</a>&nbsp;than any judicial or legislative efforts. In order to see abortion go away (as much as it can), we need to see the war as one not against abortion, but a war against poverty.</li></ol><p>Morality of abortion aside, these are the facts. This is the statistic reality we all face with abortion – and this reality does not change based on your personal disposition, values or political orientation.</p><p>The American Church needs to recognize this, and understand that there can be many ways to deal with this reality. We need to realize that President Obama’s and the Democratic Party's longstanding commitment, for instance, to providing social and economic supports for the poorest among us might indeed make a greater difference in reducing the rate of abortions than the Church's current efforts, of abstinence-only education, legal maneuvering, and defunding insurance coverage for abortion procedures. Demonizing those who disagree doesn’t change the reality, nor does it bring us closer to working out a real solution to America's high abortion rates.</p><p>We need to seek a conciliatory center, one that’s good for all of us – and especially for the women and families facing circumstances which may lead them to choose an abortion. This is what we&nbsp;<em>need</em>. Instead, most “pro life” (and, equally, “pro choice”) efforts have ignored these basic facts, and their advocates have allowed the conversation to devolve into a culture war.</p><p>What we instead need to seek is a common ground between these two ultimately insufficient labels. We need to seek, as Notre Dame president Reverend John I. Jenkins said, a place of conciliatory dialogue where we can approach each other and the matter at hand “with love and a generous spirit.”</p>]]></content:encoded>
