      <title>Should Teachers Carry Guns?</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/12/should-teachers-carry-guns</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Not a week has gone by and the counter-gun control argument has already tossed courtesy aside and begun blaming everything <em>but</em> the ready availability of guns for the Sandy Hook shooting. First, mental health – and those who work in mental health services – took the rap; it's not guns, it's just crazy people who kill. Then, out came the video game excuse, as National Rifle Association spokesman Wayne LaPierre – who apparently still lives in the 1990s – took to a news conference <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/22/us/nra-calls-for-armed-guards-at-schools.html?&amp;pagewanted=all">to blame</a></p>

<p>I'm particularly struck by this argument from Charlotte Allen at </p>

<p>Responding to a ludicrous charge by the <em><a href="http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/335996/newtown-answers-nro-symposium">National Review</a></em> that the Sandy Hook shooting was allowed to happen because "there were no men around in the school [...] creating a 'feminized setting' in which 'helpless passivity is the norm'" (never mind how preposterous all of that is), New Yorker writer Amy Davidson</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>As the mother of a twelve-year-old who might be described as husky, or at least big for his age, I do teach him that he has an extra responsibility to, for example, stand up for littler kids who are bullied—to never be a bystander. But I greatly resent the idea that he should throw himself in front of a bullet because a grown congressman isn’t brave enough to throw an N.R.A. lobbyist out of his office.</p>
</blockquote>]]></content:encoded>
