    <item>
      <title>The Enduring Popularity of LEGO (and a Long Rant About Other Things)</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/12/the-enduring-popularity-of-lego-and-a-long-rant-about-other-things</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Writing for NPR's Planet Money blog, <a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/money/2012/12/13/167055503/why-legos-are-so-expensive-and-so-popular">Chana Joffe-Walt takes a look</a> at why LEGO sets are so expensive – and yet have remained so popular over the years. It's a solid piece, as Joffe-Walt also shares from an interview with David Robertson, author of the forthcoming book <em>Brick by Brick: How LEGO Reinvented its Innovation System and Conquered the Toy Industry</em>. (You do have to ignore the article's egregious violations of the correct pluralization of LEGO, though. Hint: <a href="http://english.stackexchange.com/questions/10839/legos-not-lego">it's <em>not</em> "Legos"</a>.) </p>

<p>This passage in particular, though, stuck out at me:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The Star Wars blocks were wildly successful. So Lego kept going — it licensed Indiana Jones, Winnie the Pooh, Toy Story and Harry Potter.</p>
  
  <p>Sales of these products have been huge for Lego. More important, the experience has taught the company that what kids wanted to do with the blocks was tell stories. Lego makes or licenses the stories they want to tell.</p>
  
  <p>And kids know the difference.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Thast's it. Those four short sentences manage to capture so many great things so perfectly. They nail what LEGO is about. They also nail the enduring allure of Star Wars. But they also nail something more fundamental about our understanding of childhood and the role of children's toys.</p>

<h2 id="yeahyeahsoyourkidplayswithuttercrap">Yeah, yeah, so your kid plays with utter crap</h2>

<p>As adults, we often find ourselves bemoaning "the commercialization of childhood." We wish – all too readily – that children would just play with simpler and less expensive toys, and exchange the "overstimulation" of videogames for a Normal Rockwell pace of life. It's just become accepted to assume that children's creativity and imagination are associated with children's toys that are more "open-ended," nondescript, non-commercial, and that anything else is crap: maybe not that harmful for kids, but certainly not that good for them either. Especially if it <a href="http://commercialfreechildhood.org/sites/default/files/levin_childrensrights.pdf">has a brand, is Justin Bieber, or wears pretend gogo boots</a>. When we walk down the toy aisle, a good parent's instinct is to seek out the "educational toys" and books – and to avoid anything that looks too cheap, too derived from popular culture or media, or just too out of our comfort zone.</p>

<p>Fundamentally, the adult culture surrounding the American middle class childhood experience today is about one basic task: determining what things are "good" for children and what things are "bad" for children, and then maximizing the good and minimizing the bad.</p>

<p>The "good bad good bad!" agenda is widespread – and so seemingly innocuous that we aren't often conscious of our participation in it. Yet it's there. I see it every day in the expectations of the (very bright) young undergraduate students I work with, many of whom at least initially claim that they want to with kids so that they can "save childhood" from an unrelenting barrage of popular culture, video games, and media. (I talk them out of that misconception pretty quickly.) It's also there in the social pressure parents extend to each other: the disapproving looks at the playground suggestively questioning why you aren't giving your child organic juice instead of Kool-Aid. It's there in the "10 ways to [improve] your child!" lists and the fortune cookie wisdom within parenting magazines and talk shows, and there in the curriculum taught to every future teacher of America within their child development classes, and in the constant, endless bemoaning of society expressed within a million slightly-reworded versions of the same damn newspaper op-ed.</p>

<p>It's also there in the questions we ask, both of children and of ourselves. Why do kids need Angry Birds when they can go outside and see real birds? Why must my child spend so many countless hours playing this stupid Pirates of the Carribean video game when they could just read "Treasure Island"? Why do kids even need action figures and Barbie dolls, when they could just – you know – make one with a stick or something?</p>

<p>We constantly, implicitly prioritize the "stuff" of childhood, even when we're not aware of it. Outdoors are better than indoors. It's better to live in the suburbs than the city. Books are better than TV and video games, and old books are better than new books. (Especially those horrible new, sex-ridden YA ones.) If the Hardy Boys and Nancy Drew were good enough for us, they should be plenty good for kids these days. </p>

<p>Lori Pickert wrote something similar to this in 2009, explaining why she didn't ever worry about her children's screen time:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>There’s a billboard in my town that makes me grind my teeth into dust. It shows a kid’s hands holding, on the left, a video-game controller and, on the right, a turtle. Then it says something along the lines of “unplug”.</p>
  
  <p>I was ranting about it the other day and one of my sons rolled his eyes (nicely) and said, “Mooooom, they’re just telling people to, you know, go outside more.” And yes, I get that. But they are doing it in a way that makes me crazy.</p>
  
  <p>The whole either/or mentality is what gets to me. By positing the game controller against the turtle, the message is “video games: bad, playing outside: good.” Why isn’t this a good way to get kids outdoors? Because if they reject the left side of that equation, they may automatically reject the right side. This kind of shaming argument runs a serious risk of turning kids off the outdoors.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>She labels this argument, in short, <a href="http://project-based-homeschooling.com/camp-creek-blog/defense-reading-which-should-need-no-defense">the "books are broccoli" approach</a>. As Lori describes: "We are sending all kinds of subtle, between-the-lines messages about what’s broccoli and what’s candy." Every day. </p>

<p>And you know what it's really about? Control. Adults want to control kids. They want them to get into Harvard, or they want them to score the winning touchdown in their football team. They want them to experience the same kind of childhood as they remember. One of my (very bright) students shared this quote with me recently: "Children are not coloring books. You can't simply fill them in with all your favorite colors."</p>]]></content:encoded>
