    <item>
      <title>Why Aren't Children Fit Anymore?</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/10/why-arent-children-fit-anymore</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>http://rethinkingchildhood.com/2012/01/13/good-childhood/</p>

<p>Gretchen Reynolds, writing for the New York Times, points to a new research review published last week that examined the effectiveness of special physical fitness programs for children:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>In each case, the investigators had expected that the programs would increase the children’s overall daily physical activity.</p>
  
  <p>That didn’t happen, as the review’s authors found when they carefully parsed outcomes. The American students, for instance, increased their overall daily physical activity by about five minutes per day. But only during the first few weeks of the program; by the end, their overall daily physical activity had returned to about where it had been before the program began. The wee Scottish participants actually became less physically active over all on the days when they had the 30-minute play sessions.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>To someone who spends time with kids and thinks critically about their lives, I have to say this would seem obvious: kids don't benefit from these programs because they're boring. You'd need to put "play sessions" up above in very clear air-quotes, because really, they're anything but; they're patronizing and heavy-handed, and almost exclusively guided by adults. What kid wants to spend even <em>more</em> time during their day being told what to do by an adult – especially when that cuts into what would otherwise be playtime with friends (as Reynolds appropriately points out)?</p>

<p>Simply stated, most of these interventions to address children's physical fitness do very little to address the thing that's actually much more important: the culture and social conditions around children's lives. These play a much bigger role in determining fitness levels than just children's own attitudes about fitness. We so often treat children's physical inactivity as an isolated problem – and one that's mostly their fault – when the reality is really the exact opposite.</p>

<p><strong>The first lesson here is that family culture matters.</strong> The amount of a child's levels of physical activity <a href="http://www.ijbnpa.org/content/8/1/17">correlates very closely</a> with that of their parents: active kids tend to have active parents. That might seem obvious, but in practice it's hardly ever considered within intervention efforts. It's not a completely causal relationship – you can have very active kids from very inactive families, and inactive kids from very active families – but it is a crucial bellwether indicator of the social and physical conditions around children's lives that encourage physical activity. If you're a kid and all you ever see your parents do is bum around on the couch after work – and they hardly ever play or step foot outside (save to walk to the minivan) – you're very likely to follow suit. In fact, it'd be hard not to. Which leads us to the second lesson.</p>

<p><strong>The other part of this reality is that children face incredible social and physical barriers to play and physical activity.</strong>  In almost all cases, children really do lack the time, space, and freedom to play. </p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Time:</strong> Children's schedules have been filled with organized sports, activities, and other obligations, not to mention homework – all of which drastically eat into the amount of time they have that's completely their own.</li>
<li><strong>Space:</strong> How often do you see an interesting backyard? A real one, with messy, open-ended materials like treehouses and lumber, perhaps some sand, water, and fire – all freely available for kids to use when they want and for what they want? At best, most backyards might have a swingset designed for six-year-olds and maybe a trampoline. That might suffice for a while, but we all need new stimulation every now and then – and we like it even more when we have some control over our environment, and know : when we can play big and build messy, and when we know that it'll always be there for us to come back to.</li>
</ul>

<p>When all of their time obligations are said and done, what 
* Freedom:</p>

<p>amount of time when they're in control of their lives.</p>

<p>There's a reason that after-school programs</p>

<p>with inactive parents are also much more likely to have more barriers to play and physical activity; parents might</p>

<p>parents might not appreciate its value, they might not provide regular opportunities for it in children's environments and schedules, and they might not really foster a family culture</p>]]></content:encoded>
