    <item>
      <title>Being an Atelierista in a Reggio Inspired School</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/being-an-atelierista-in-a-reggio-inspired-school</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It can often be confusing what kind of a role the 'Atelierista', or Art Studio teacher, has within a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reggio_Emilia_approach">Reggio Emilia-inspired</a> school – and just how much of it does or should involve 'direct instruction'. On the one hand, the arts are so integrally regarded in the approach as languages of exploration and expression for children – so it makes sense that the proficiency children have in these different art mediums is a vital consideration for teachers. Yet within the Reggio 'way', it is so often the children's own inquiries, play, and interests that guide and direct the classroom's emergent curriculum – the approach is, in simple terms, the antithesis of 'direct', teacher-driven instruction. How can proficiency be pursued, while respecting children as the center of the school?</p>

<p>Atelierista Anna provides a wonderful consideaiton of this.</p>]]></content:encoded>
