    <item>
      <title>Alleged Child Labor Abuses at a Chinese Samsung Factory</title>
      <link>/blog/2012/8/alleged-child-labor-abuses-at-a-chinese-samsung-factory</link>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Child labor is, without a doubt, an explosive and sensational topic for the press to cover. The latest child labor-related news – following a string of (later confirmed untrue) allegations against Apple Inc. earlier this year and last – is that electronics company Samsung&nbsp;</p><p>There is no doubt that serious abuses against these students took place, at least based on the evidence in <a href="http://chinalaborwatch.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/samsung8-27.pdf">China Labor Watch's report</a>.&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Signing contracts with teachers, not students – conflating the ambiguity around "internship". Often lax supervision by teachers, possible expoitation for the teachers' own gain. Bottom line: is the final benefit here supposed to be for the students themselves – is this a learning experience, where they aren't held to the same expectations or standards – or the adults? Motivation is everything, in this case.</li><li>Excessiveness. Hours, etc. </li></ul>]]></content:encoded>
